RNAseq methodDifferential expression analyses

Requirement description

Remove confounding factors such as age, gender, race, batch, etc. that affect RNAseq expression levels. The method is described in the differential expression analyses section of the article. The result chart can be compared with two heat maps

https://academic.oup.com/hmg/article/22/24/5001/568201

fromhttps://academic.oup.com/hmg/article/22/24/5001/568201

Evaluation of logistic regression models and effect of covariates for casecontrol study in RNA-Seq analysishttps://link.springer.com/article/10.1186%2Fs12859-017-1498-y

DESeq2edgeRlimmadesign matrix

Or reference: Evaluation of logistic regression models and effect of covariates for casecontrol study in RNA-Seq analysis< https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186%2Fs12859 -017-1498-y>

**Off topic: In the example text, this multivariate logistic regression approach is used to consider the influence of covariates. Personally, I think adding these variables to the design matrix of some mature differential expression algorithms (such as DESeq2, edgeR, limma) may be more stable.

  • DESeq2design

2016BiostatisticsMethods that remove batch effects while retaining group differences may lead to exaggerated confidence in downstream analyseshttps://t.zsxq.com/3j2beI6

Application scenarios

Used for differential expression analysis. Large scale sequencing data is often mixed with various covariates, which affect differential gene screening. There are two common strategies:

-Strategy one is to remove these confounding factors, which is adopted in the example text; -Strategy 2: Incorporate these factors into the design of DESeq2 and recommend this strategy.

The following article discusses in detail the drawbacks of the first approach and provides guidance for practical operation: 2016 BiostatisticsMethods that remove batch effects while retaining group differences may lead to exaggerated confidence in downstream analyses< https://t.zsxq.com/3j2beI6 >

Custom functions

# Display progress of differential expression analysis
# index: Current processing index
# totalN: Total number of items to process
# breakN: Number of progress updates to display
display.progress = function ( index, totalN, breakN=20) {
  
  # Display progress percentage at regular intervals
  if ( index %% ceiling(totalN/breakN)  ==0  ) {
    cat(paste(round(index*100/totalN), "% ", sep=""))
  }
}    

# Multivariable linear regression for differential expression analysis considering covariates
# emat: FPKMTPMcountInput expression matrix with genes as rows and samples as columns
# sinfo: Sample information including groups for comparison and covariates
# res.var: response variable10Response variable for logistic regression, should be binary (1/0)
# cov.var: covariate variableageCovariate variables to adjust for in the model
# logtrans: log2TRUEWhether to log2 transform gene expression values, default is TRUE
# isorder: FDRTRUEWhether to sort results by FDR, default is TRUE
multilinearDE <- function(emat = NULL, sinfo = NULL, res.var = NULL, cov.var = NULL, logtrans = T, isorder = T) {
  
  # IDValidate sample IDs match between expression matrix and sample information
  if(!identical(colnames(emat),rownames(sinfo))) {
    stop("Error! The sampleIDs are not matched in emat and sinfo!\n")
  }
  
  # 01Ensure response variable is binary with both 0 and 1 present
  if(sum(is.element(c("1","0"),as.character(sinfo[,res.var]))) != 2) { 
    stop("Error! The response variable must be 1 and 0, please transform it first!\n")
  }
  
  # Validate all variables exist in sample information
  if(!all(is.element(c(res.var,cov.var),colnames(sinfo)))) {
    stop("Error! All the variable should be included in sinfo with the same label name!\n")
  }
  
  # Initialize result variables
  p.gene <- fc <- log2fc <- c() 
  for (i in 1:nrow(emat)) {
    
    # Display progress
    display.progress(index = i,totalN = nrow(emat)) 
    
    gene = rownames(emat)[i]
    
    # logtranslog2Log transform expression values if specified
    if(logtrans) {
      tmp <- cbind.data.frame(gene = log2(t(emat[gene,]) + 1), sinfo) 
    } else { tmp <- cbind.data.frame(gene = t(emat[gene,]), sinfo) }
    colnames(tmp)[1] <- "gene"
    
    # Construct logistic regression formula
    f <-  as.formula(paste(res.var, "~", paste(c("gene",cov.var), collapse = ' + '))) 
    
    # Perform binomial logistic regression
    model_glm <- glm(f, data = tmp, family = "binomial") 
    # pExtract p-value for gene expression
    p.gene <- c(p.gene,summary(model_glm)$coefficients["gene",4]) 
    
    # Calculate fold change between groups
    a <- as.numeric(emat[gene,which(tmp$class == "1"),])
    b <- as.numeric(emat[gene,which(tmp$class == "0"),])
    fc <- c(fc,mean(a)/mean(b)) 
    log2fc <- c(log2fc,log2(mean(a)/mean(b))) 
  }
  
  # Generate differential expression results table
  outTab <- data.frame(gene = rownames(emat), 
                       fc = fc,
                       log2fc = log2fc,
                       p.value = p.gene, 
                       fdr = p.adjust(p.gene,method = "fdr"), 
                       stringsAsFactors = F)
  
  # isorderFDRSort results by FDR if specified
  if(isorder) { 
    outTab <- outTab[order(outTab$fdr),]
    return(outTab)
  } else {return(outTab)}
}

Multivariate logistic regression to determine significant transcripts

# Create age squared as an additional covariate
# To capture potential nonlinear effects of age
sinfo$age2 <- sinfo$age^2 

# Perform multivariable linear regression for differential expression analysis
# Adjust for age, age squared, and gender as covariates
outTab <- multilinearDE(emat = emat,
                        sinfo = sinfo,
                        res.var = "class",        #  vs Response variable: immune subtype vs others
                        cov.var = c("age","age2","sex"),  # Covariates: age, age squared, and gender
                        logtrans = T,             # log2Log-transform expression values
                        isorder = F)              # FDRDo not sort results by FDR

Start drawing

View the typing effect by drawing a heat map

# Select differentially expressed genes
# FDR < 0.05  log2FC > 2Criteria: FDR < 0.05 and absolute log2 fold change > 2
degs <- outTab[which(outTab$fdr < 0.05 & abs(outTab$log2fc) > 2), "gene"]

# Create sample annotation for heatmap
# classLabel samples by class variable
annCol <- data.frame(class=sinfo$class,row.names = rownames(sinfo),stringsAsFactors = F)
annCol$class <- ifelse(annCol$class == 1,"Immune","Others") 

# Set colors for heatmap annotations
# ImmuneOthersBlue for Immune group, yellow for Others
annColors <- list("class"=c("Immune"="#2874C5","Others"="#EABF00"))

# log2Log2 transform expression matrix
indata <- log2(emat + 1)

# Hierarchical clustering for samples
# ward.DEuclidean distance with ward.D linkage
hcg <- hclust(distanceMatrix(as.matrix(t(indata[degs,rownames(sinfo)])), "euclidean"), "ward.D")

# Hierarchical clustering for genes
# ward.DEuclidean distance with ward.D linkage
hcs <- hclust(distanceMatrix(as.matrix(indata[degs,rownames(sinfo)]), "euclidean"), "ward.D")

# Standardize data and truncate extreme values
# [-3,3]Standardize and limit values to [-3, 3]
plotdata <- t(scale(t(indata)))
plotdata[plotdata >= 3] <- 3
plotdata[plotdata <= -3] <- -3

# Plot heatmap of differentially expressed genes
# pheatmapCreate annotated heatmap with pheatmap
pheatmap(plotdata[degs,],
         annotation_col = annCol,          # Add sample annotations
         annotation_colors = annColors,    # Set annotation colors
         cluster_cols = hcs,               # Use precomputed column clustering
         show_rownames = F,                # Hide gene names
         show_colnames = F,                # Hide sample names
         cluster_rows = hcg,               # Use precomputed row clustering
         labels_col = NULL,                # No column labels
         labels_row = NULL,                # No row labels
         filename = "heatmap for DEGs.pdf") # PDFSave as PDF

immune others

From the heatmap, it can be seen that the differentially expressed genes have effectively separated the immune and other subtypes, and the effect of removing confounding factors is also good.
